gcn_e4a5cac31481497c = claim(
    "Using ab initio molecular dynamics (AIMD) sampling of finite-temperature atomic configurations for bulk CsPbBr₃ at temperature T = 300 K in the canonical (NVT) ensemble with a Nosé–Hoover thermostat on a 3×3×3 pseudocubic supercell (135 atoms) and a 1 fs time step, and computing single-point electronic structures on a representative equilibrated AIMD snapshot with the Heyd–Scuseria–Ernzerhof hybrid functional including spin–orbit coupling (HSE–SOC, where HSE denotes the screened hybrid functional of Heyd, Scuseria, and Ernzerhof and SOC denotes spin–orbit coupling) using a hybrid mixing parameter α = 0.54 chosen so that the calculated band gap E_g = 2.37 eV matches the experimental room-temperature band gap, the direction-averaged hole effective mass computed for that room-temperature AIMD configuration is m_h = 0.265 m_0 (where m_0 is the free-electron mass). This computed m_h = 0.265 m_0 agrees with the angle-resolved photoemission spectroscopy (ARPES) measurement of m_h = 0.26 ± 0.02 m_0 reported for CsPbBr₃, and this agreement is obtained without introducing any extra hole into the supercell (i.e., without polaron formation); therefore the ARPES-measured hole effective mass can be explained by thermal-lattice fluctuations alone under these simulated room-temperature, bulk-like conditions. [@Zhao2025]",
    title="Finite-T AIMD matches ARPES mass",
    lkm_id="gcn_e4a5cac31481497c",
    lkm_original="Using ab initio molecular dynamics (AIMD) sampling of finite-temperature atomic configurations for bulk CsPbBr₃ at temperature T = 300 K in the canonical (NVT) ensemble with a Nosé–Hoover thermostat on a 3×3×3 pseudocubic supercell (135 atoms) and a 1 fs time step, and computing single-point electronic structures on a representative equilibrated AIMD snapshot with the Heyd–Scuseria–Ernzerhof hybrid functional including spin–orbit coupling (HSE–SOC, where HSE denotes the screened hybrid functional of Heyd, Scuseria, and Ernzerhof and SOC denotes spin–orbit coupling) using a hybrid mixing parameter α = 0.54 chosen so that the calculated band gap E_g = 2.37 eV matches the experimental room-temperature band gap, the direction-averaged hole effective mass computed for that room-temperature AIMD configuration is m_h = 0.265 m_0 (where m_0 is the free-electron mass). This computed m_h = 0.265 m_0 agrees with the angle-resolved photoemission spectroscopy (ARPES) measurement of m_h = 0.26 ± 0.02 m_0 reported for CsPbBr₃, and this agreement is obtained without introducing any extra hole into the supercell (i.e., without polaron formation); therefore the ARPES-measured hole effective mass can be explained by thermal-lattice fluctuations alone under these simulated room-temperature, bulk-like conditions.",
    source_paper="paper:1096665743648358400",
    provenance_source="lkm",
)
gcn_c24c81b8a5fe413c = claim(
    "Let an ARPES measurement of the valence-band dispersion at temperature T = 300 K produce an effective, thermally averaged band curvature corresponding to an experimental hole effective mass m_h^exp. The proposition is: a single representative equilibrated pseudocubic atomic configuration sampled from AIMD at T = 300 K (3×3×3 supercell, 135 atoms, Nosé–Hoover thermostat, 1 fs timestep) provides an electronic band structure whose unfolded valence-band curvature equals the ARPES thermally averaged curvature within typical experimental uncertainty; equivalently, ensemble averaging over many AIMD configurations is not required to reproduce the ARPES-measured m_h^exp for bulk CsPbBr₃ when using the representative-snapshot-plus-tuned-α procedure. [@Zhao2025]",
    title="Single AIMD snapshot represents ARPES average",
    lkm_id="gcn_c24c81b8a5fe413c",
    lkm_original="Let an ARPES measurement of the valence-band dispersion at temperature T = 300 K produce an effective, thermally averaged band curvature corresponding to an experimental hole effective mass m_h^exp. The proposition is: a single representative equilibrated pseudocubic atomic configuration sampled from AIMD at T = 300 K (3×3×3 supercell, 135 atoms, Nosé–Hoover thermostat, 1 fs timestep) provides an electronic band structure whose unfolded valence-band curvature equals the ARPES thermally averaged curvature within typical experimental uncertainty; equivalently, ensemble averaging over many AIMD configurations is not required to reproduce the ARPES-measured m_h^exp for bulk CsPbBr₃ when using the representative-snapshot-plus-tuned-α procedure.",
    source_paper="paper:1096665743648358400",
    provenance_source="lkm",
)
gcn_43c66f240368417e = claim(
    "Let Brillouin-zone unfolding denote the procedure that maps supercell eigenvalues and computed spectral weights onto the primitive-cell Brillouin zone to produce an energy–momentum colormap for extracting band dispersions and effective masses. The proposition is: the unfolded bulk spectral intensity and dispersion obtained from a 3×3×3 supercell HSE–SOC(α = 0.54) calculation can be directly compared to ARPES measurements of the valence-band dispersion of CsPbBr₃ without applying explicit corrections for photoemission matrix-element effects, surface electronic-structure differences, extrinsic surface disorder, or ARPES finite probing-depth effects; therefore, agreement between an unfolded bulk effective mass and an ARPES effective mass is taken as evidence that the bulk thermal-structure model captures the experimentally observed dispersion. [@Zhao2025]",
    title="Bulk unfolding comparable to ARPES",
    lkm_id="gcn_43c66f240368417e",
    lkm_original="Let Brillouin-zone unfolding denote the procedure that maps supercell eigenvalues and computed spectral weights onto the primitive-cell Brillouin zone to produce an energy–momentum colormap for extracting band dispersions and effective masses. The proposition is: the unfolded bulk spectral intensity and dispersion obtained from a 3×3×3 supercell HSE–SOC(α = 0.54) calculation can be directly compared to ARPES measurements of the valence-band dispersion of CsPbBr₃ without applying explicit corrections for photoemission matrix-element effects, surface electronic-structure differences, extrinsic surface disorder, or ARPES finite probing-depth effects; therefore, agreement between an unfolded bulk effective mass and an ARPES effective mass is taken as evidence that the bulk thermal-structure model captures the experimentally observed dispersion.",
    source_paper="paper:1096665743648358400",
    provenance_source="lkm",
)
gcn_1c2bf8f398f243f9 = claim(
    "Consider AIMD trajectories used to sample finite-temperature atomic configurations for a material with a soft anharmonic lattice. The proposition is: performing AIMD structural sampling with the Perdew–Burke–Ernzerhof (PBE) generalized-gradient exchange-correlation functional using a 3×3×3 supercell, a Nosé–Hoover thermostat sampling the canonical ensemble, and a 1 fs timestep yields a structural ensemble whose statistical distribution of atomic positions is sufficiently accurate for subsequent single-point HSE–SOC (with tuned α) electronic-structure calculations to produce reliable thermally renormalized unfolded band dispersions and effective masses; in particular, any systematic biases in equilibrium lattice parameters or force constants introduced by PBE do not materially change the unfolded band curvatures obtained from representative AIMD snapshots evaluated with HSE–SOC. [@Zhao2025]",
    title="PBE AIMD sampling is adequate",
    lkm_id="gcn_1c2bf8f398f243f9",
    lkm_original="Consider AIMD trajectories used to sample finite-temperature atomic configurations for a material with a soft anharmonic lattice. The proposition is: performing AIMD structural sampling with the Perdew–Burke–Ernzerhof (PBE) generalized-gradient exchange-correlation functional using a 3×3×3 supercell, a Nosé–Hoover thermostat sampling the canonical ensemble, and a 1 fs timestep yields a structural ensemble whose statistical distribution of atomic positions is sufficiently accurate for subsequent single-point HSE–SOC (with tuned α) electronic-structure calculations to produce reliable thermally renormalized unfolded band dispersions and effective masses; in particular, any systematic biases in equilibrium lattice parameters or force constants introduced by PBE do not materially change the unfolded band curvatures obtained from representative AIMD snapshots evaluated with HSE–SOC.",
    source_paper="paper:1096665743648358400",
    provenance_source="lkm",
)
gfac_9b8940e7a4c141b2 = deduction(
    [gcn_c24c81b8a5fe413c, gcn_43c66f240368417e, gcn_1c2bf8f398f243f9],
    gcn_e4a5cac31481497c,
    reason="1. State the upstream results to be used as known starting points: (i) conclusion 2 — thermal lattice fluctuations at $T=300\\\\,$K substantially enhance carrier effective masses in $CsPbBr_{3}$, and (ii) conclusion 6 — $CsPbBr_{3}$ exhibits strong lattice anharmonicity and large low-frequency vibrational modes that produce the thermal fluctuations; treat these as established for the following comparison with experiment.\n\n2. Describe the finite-temperature computational protocol used to obtain the room-temperature band structure and effective mass: perform ab initio molecular dynamics (AIMD) at $T=300\\\\,$K in the canonical ensemble (NVT) with the Nosé–Hoover thermostat to sample finite-temperature atomic configurations for a 3×3×3 pseudocubic supercell containing 135 atoms, using the Perdew–Burke–Ernzerhof (PBE) exchange-correlation functional to generate structural trajectories with a time step of 1 fs; select a representative equilibrated pseudocubic AIMD configuration and compute the electronic structure for that configuration using the HSE hybrid functional including spin–orbit coupling (HSE–SOC) with the hybrid mixing parameter $\\\\alpha=0.54$ chosen to reproduce the experimental room-temperature band gap $E_{\\\\text{g}}=2.37\\\\,$eV.\n[21]\nFig. 1\n\n3. Define the computed observable: the direction-averaged hole effective mass $m_{h}$ is extracted from the unfolded HSE–SOC band structure of the representative $T=300\\\\,$K AIMD configuration (define \"unfolded\" as the Brillouin-zone unfolding procedure used to map the supercell band structure onto the primitive-cell Brillouin zone).\n[27]\n\n4. Report the computed numerical result from the AIMD $T=300\\\\,$K HSE–SOC calculation with $\\\\alpha=0.54$: the direction-averaged hole effective mass is $m_{h}=0.265\\\\,m_{0}$, where $m_{0}$ denotes the electron rest mass; emphasize that this calculation was performed in the absence of any injected carrier (i.e., no extra hole was introduced).\nTable I\n\n5. Compare the computed $m_{h}=0.265\\\\,m_{0}$ to the ARPES experimental measurement reported by Puppin et al., which is $0.26 \\\\pm 0.02\\\\,m_{0}$; state that the computed value agrees with the experimental ARPES value within the experimental uncertainty.\n[14]\n\n6. Note the additional computational observation (from the authors' explicit hole-injection tests and conclusion 4) that introducing an extra hole into the AIMD supercell at $T=300\\\\,$K does not produce localized in-gap states nor materially change the valence-band dispersion; therefore the agreement between computed and measured hole masses is achieved in the absence of any polaron-induced mass enhancement.\nFig. 3\n\n7. Conclude that the experimentally observed hole effective mass can be explained by thermal-lattice fluctuations alone as captured by the finite-temperature HSE–SOC calculation (AIMD $T=300\\\\,$K, $\\\\alpha=0.54$), and therefore there is no ARPES-based evidence from this comparison for a significant polaron-induced enhancement of the hole effective mass in $CsPbBr_{3}$ under the studied conditions.",
    prior=0.95,
)
gcn_78dd3a5f6fb84289 = claim(
    "Introducing one extra hole (removing one electron) into an equilibrated 3×3×3 pseudocubic AIMD supercell (135 atoms) of bulk CsPbBr₃ sampled at T = 300 K and recomputing the electronic structure with HSE–SOC using α = 0.54 produces no localized in-gap electronic states and causes no substantial change in the unfolded valence-band dispersions relative to the corresponding polaron-free AIMD calculation; the absence of such localized gap states or strongly localized valence-band perturbations in these finite-supercell HSE–SOC calculations indicates that thermally stabilized small-hole polarons are not observed under these simulated bulk-like room-temperature conditions. [@Zhao2025]",
    title="No small-hole polaron in 300 K AIMD",
    lkm_id="gcn_78dd3a5f6fb84289",
    lkm_original="Introducing one extra hole (removing one electron) into an equilibrated 3×3×3 pseudocubic AIMD supercell (135 atoms) of bulk CsPbBr₃ sampled at T = 300 K and recomputing the electronic structure with HSE–SOC using α = 0.54 produces no localized in-gap electronic states and causes no substantial change in the unfolded valence-band dispersions relative to the corresponding polaron-free AIMD calculation; the absence of such localized gap states or strongly localized valence-band perturbations in these finite-supercell HSE–SOC calculations indicates that thermally stabilized small-hole polarons are not observed under these simulated bulk-like room-temperature conditions.",
    source_paper="paper:1096665743648358400",
    provenance_source="lkm",
)
gcn_82d0efc0c1024ec8 = claim(
    "Define a polaron as a charge carrier (here a hole) that self-localizes through a local lattice distortion, producing a localized in-gap electronic state or a strongly localized perturbation of the valence-band dispersion. Consider the following explicit first-principles simulation protocol: start from a 3×3×3 pseudocubic AIMD supercell (135 atoms) equilibrated at T = 300 K, remove one electron to introduce a single extra hole while applying any standard neutralizing background required for charged-supercell calculations, and compute the electronic structure of the charged supercell with HSE–SOC using α = 0.54. The proposition is: if a thermodynamically stable small hole polaron exists under bulk-like conditions at T = 300 K, then the stated simulation procedure (finite supercell of this size, the HSE–SOC electronic-structure method with the indicated α, and an AIMD-sampled atomic configuration) is sufficient to produce a detectable localized in-gap state or a stabilized localized lattice distortion; conversely, absence of such signatures in the described simulation implies that small polarons are not stabilized under the simulated conditions. [@Zhao2025]",
    title="Small-polaron simulation criterion",
    lkm_id="gcn_82d0efc0c1024ec8",
    lkm_original="Define a polaron as a charge carrier (here a hole) that self-localizes through a local lattice distortion, producing a localized in-gap electronic state or a strongly localized perturbation of the valence-band dispersion. Consider the following explicit first-principles simulation protocol: start from a 3×3×3 pseudocubic AIMD supercell (135 atoms) equilibrated at T = 300 K, remove one electron to introduce a single extra hole while applying any standard neutralizing background required for charged-supercell calculations, and compute the electronic structure of the charged supercell with HSE–SOC using α = 0.54. The proposition is: if a thermodynamically stable small hole polaron exists under bulk-like conditions at T = 300 K, then the stated simulation procedure (finite supercell of this size, the HSE–SOC electronic-structure method with the indicated α, and an AIMD-sampled atomic configuration) is sufficient to produce a detectable localized in-gap state or a stabilized localized lattice distortion; conversely, absence of such signatures in the described simulation implies that small polarons are not stabilized under the simulated conditions.",
    source_paper="paper:1096665743648358400",
    provenance_source="lkm",
)
gfac_f1605d37c7074f6b = deduction(
    [gcn_82d0efc0c1024ec8],
    gcn_78dd3a5f6fb84289,
    reason="1. Treat as known (from conclusion 6) that $CsPbBr_{3}$ at room temperature exhibits strong lattice anharmonicity and large thermal lattice fluctuations; use this as the structural context for hole-injection simulations.\n\n2. Describe the computational procedure used to test the effect of an injected hole: start from an equilibrated AIMD supercell representing a room-temperature configuration (define \"AIMD supercell\" as the 3×3×3 pseudocubic supercell with 135 atoms sampled from the $T=300\\\\,$K AIMD run), explicitly remove one electron (introduce a single extra hole) into that supercell, and recompute the electronic band structure using the HSE hybrid functional with spin-orbit coupling (HSE–SOC) and with the hybrid mixing parameter $\\\\alpha=0.54$ (the value determined to reproduce the experimental $E_{\\\\text{g}}=2.37\\\\,$eV at finite temperature).\nFig. 3\n[20]\n\n3. State the direct computational observation: the unfolded band structure computed for the equilibrated $T=300\\\\,$K supercell with an extra hole shows no formation of localized in-gap states (define \"localized in-gap states\" as electronic states whose energy lies within the band gap and whose wavefunctions are spatially localized around specific lattice distortions), and the unfolded valence-band dispersions remain essentially unchanged relative to the polaron-free AIMD configuration (i.e., negligible change in valence-band curvature and dispersion).\nFig. 3\n\n4. Report that the authors explicitly checked for hole localization (define \"hole localization\" as a self-trapped hole leading to a local lattice distortion that stabilizes a bound electronic state) and found no evidence for a stabilized localized hole or small-polaron formation in the simulated room-temperature conditions; therefore the addition of an extra hole produces negligible additional renormalization of the band structure beyond the thermally induced effects already present in the polaron-free AIMD configuration.\n[29]\n\n5. Conclude that explicit simulation of a single injected hole at $T=300\\\\,$K does not produce localized gap states and does not stabilize small polarons in $CsPbBr_{3}$ under the simulated conditions, and therefore small-polaron formation is not observed in these finite-temperature, HSE–SOC calculations.",
    prior=0.95,
)
gcn_3f848904ab0d4b48 = claim(
    "Thermal lattice fluctuations in bulk CsPbBr₃ at T = 300 K substantially renormalize band-edge curvatures: comparing unfolded HSE–SOC band structures computed on a representative equilibrated AIMD configuration at 300 K (with α = 0.54 chosen to reproduce the experimental E_g = 2.37 eV) to the unfolded HSE–SOC band structure computed on the ideal cubic lattice at 0 K using α = 0.74 (the value required on the ideal lattice to reproduce E_g = 2.37 eV), the direction-averaged electron effective mass increases by approximately 57% and the direction-averaged hole effective mass increases by approximately 79%; numerically, the direction-averaged hole mass changes from m_h ≈ 0.149 m_0 for the ideal cubic 0 K calculation with α = 0.74 to m_h = 0.265 m_0 for the AIMD 300 K calculation with α = 0.54. [@Zhao2025]",
    title="Thermal disorder renormalizes masses",
    lkm_id="gcn_3f848904ab0d4b48",
    lkm_original="Thermal lattice fluctuations in bulk CsPbBr₃ at T = 300 K substantially renormalize band-edge curvatures: comparing unfolded HSE–SOC band structures computed on a representative equilibrated AIMD configuration at 300 K (with α = 0.54 chosen to reproduce the experimental E_g = 2.37 eV) to the unfolded HSE–SOC band structure computed on the ideal cubic lattice at 0 K using α = 0.74 (the value required on the ideal lattice to reproduce E_g = 2.37 eV), the direction-averaged electron effective mass increases by approximately 57% and the direction-averaged hole effective mass increases by approximately 79%; numerically, the direction-averaged hole mass changes from m_h ≈ 0.149 m_0 for the ideal cubic 0 K calculation with α = 0.74 to m_h = 0.265 m_0 for the AIMD 300 K calculation with α = 0.54.",
    source_paper="paper:1096665743648358400",
    provenance_source="lkm",
)
gcn_00749f497c204b4c = claim(
    "Define an equilibrated atomic configuration as a single instantaneous atomic-coordinate snapshot selected from an AIMD trajectory sampled at T = 300 K in the canonical ensemble with a Nosé–Hoover thermostat on a 3×3×3 pseudocubic supercell (135 atoms). Let HSE–SOC(α) denote electronic-structure calculations using the Heyd–Scuseria–Ernzerhof hybrid functional including spin–orbit coupling with hybrid mixing parameter α (fraction of nonlocal Fock exchange). The proposition is: computing the unfolded electronic band structure and extracting direction-averaged effective masses from one representative equilibrated AIMD configuration using HSE–SOC(α = 0.54), where α = 0.54 is chosen so that the calculated band gap for that configuration equals the experimental room-temperature band gap E_g = 2.37 eV, yields band dispersions and direction-averaged effective masses that accurately represent the thermally averaged electronic band structure of bulk CsPbBr₃ at T = 300 K within uncertainties comparable to typical experimental error bars; thus a single snapshot plus a tuned-α HSE–SOC calculation is treated as a surrogate for ensemble averaging over thermally fluctuating structures. [@Zhao2025]",
    title="Representative snapshot mass assumption",
    lkm_id="gcn_00749f497c204b4c",
    lkm_original="Define an equilibrated atomic configuration as a single instantaneous atomic-coordinate snapshot selected from an AIMD trajectory sampled at T = 300 K in the canonical ensemble with a Nosé–Hoover thermostat on a 3×3×3 pseudocubic supercell (135 atoms). Let HSE–SOC(α) denote electronic-structure calculations using the Heyd–Scuseria–Ernzerhof hybrid functional including spin–orbit coupling with hybrid mixing parameter α (fraction of nonlocal Fock exchange). The proposition is: computing the unfolded electronic band structure and extracting direction-averaged effective masses from one representative equilibrated AIMD configuration using HSE–SOC(α = 0.54), where α = 0.54 is chosen so that the calculated band gap for that configuration equals the experimental room-temperature band gap E_g = 2.37 eV, yields band dispersions and direction-averaged effective masses that accurately represent the thermally averaged electronic band structure of bulk CsPbBr₃ at T = 300 K within uncertainties comparable to typical experimental error bars; thus a single snapshot plus a tuned-α HSE–SOC calculation is treated as a surrogate for ensemble averaging over thermally fluctuating structures.",
    source_paper="paper:1096665743648358400",
    provenance_source="lkm",
)
gcn_869be47d79c54464 = claim(
    "Let HSE–SOC(α) denote HSE calculations including SOC with fraction α of nonlocal Fock exchange. Consider two unfolded band structures: one computed on an AIMD (T = 300 K) configuration with α = 0.54 and another computed on the ideal cubic (T = 0 K) lattice with α = 0.74, where both α values were chosen so that each calculation reproduces the same experimental band gap E_g = 2.37 eV on its respective structure. The proposition is: the differences in band dispersions and effective masses between these two HSE–SOC(α) calculations can be attributed primarily to the presence or absence of thermal-lattice disorder (the atomic structural differences between the AIMD and ideal lattices) rather than to the different numerical choice of α itself or to compensating errors introduced by tuning α; in other words, tuning α to match the gap does not produce artificial changes in band curvature that would be mistaken for thermal effects in this comparison. [@Zhao2025]",
    title="Mass change attributed to disorder",
    lkm_id="gcn_869be47d79c54464",
    lkm_original="Let HSE–SOC(α) denote HSE calculations including SOC with fraction α of nonlocal Fock exchange. Consider two unfolded band structures: one computed on an AIMD (T = 300 K) configuration with α = 0.54 and another computed on the ideal cubic (T = 0 K) lattice with α = 0.74, where both α values were chosen so that each calculation reproduces the same experimental band gap E_g = 2.37 eV on its respective structure. The proposition is: the differences in band dispersions and effective masses between these two HSE–SOC(α) calculations can be attributed primarily to the presence or absence of thermal-lattice disorder (the atomic structural differences between the AIMD and ideal lattices) rather than to the different numerical choice of α itself or to compensating errors introduced by tuning α; in other words, tuning α to match the gap does not produce artificial changes in band curvature that would be mistaken for thermal effects in this comparison.",
    source_paper="paper:1096665743648358400",
    provenance_source="lkm",
)
gfac_5e7aa7aa12474862 = deduction(
    [gcn_00749f497c204b4c, gcn_869be47d79c54464],
    gcn_3f848904ab0d4b48,
    reason="1. State the upstream results to be used as known starting points: (i) conclusion 6 — $CsPbBr_{3}$ has strong lattice anharmonicity and low-frequency vibrational modes that enable large thermal lattice fluctuations at room temperature; (ii) conclusion 5 — in contrast, Si and GaAs show only minor thermal renormalization, establishing that the large thermal effects in $CsPbBr_{3}$ are exceptional.\n\n2. Define the relevant electronic effective masses: let $m_e$ denote the electron effective mass and $m_h$ denote the hole effective mass; define \"direction-averaged\" effective mass as the average of effective masses computed along the high-symmetry directions used by the authors (specifically the R–M and R–$\\\\Gamma$ directions reported in the paper), and denote the free-electron mass as $m_{0}$.\n\n3. Describe the computational comparison that yields the mass renormalization numbers: compute unfolded HSE–SOC band structures and extract direction-averaged effective masses for two cases — (A) an equilibrated AIMD configuration at $T=300\\\\,$K using $\\\\alpha=0.54$ chosen to reproduce the experimental room-temperature band gap $E_{\\\\text{g}}=2.37\\\\,$eV, and (B) the ideal cubic ($T=0\\\\,$K) lattice using $\\\\alpha=0.74$ (the value required on the ideal lattice to reproduce the same $E_{\\\\text{g}}$). The comparison isolates the effect of thermal-lattice fluctuations while keeping the band-gap benchmark fixed.\nFig. 2\n[20]\n\n4. Extract numerical values from the computed results: for the ideal cubic ($T=0\\\\,$K) case with $\\\\alpha=0.74$, the direction-averaged hole mass is $m_h \\\\approx 0.149\\\\,m_{0}$ (define $m_{0}$ as the electron rest mass), whereas for the AIMD $T=300\\\\,$K case with $\\\\alpha=0.54$, the direction-averaged hole mass is $m_h = 0.265\\\\,m_{0}$; similarly, the direction-averaged electron mass increases from $\\\\approx 0.172\\\\,m_{0}$ (ideal cubic, $\\\\alpha=0.74$) to $\\\\approx 0.263\\\\,m_{0}$ (AIMD, $\\\\alpha=0.54$), as reported in the tabulated results.\nTable I\n\n5. Compute the relative increases (define \"relative increase\" as $100\\\\times (m_{\\\\text{finite T}}-m_{0\\\\,\\\\text{ideal}})/m_{0\\\\,\\\\text{ideal}}\\\\%$): for electrons, the direction-averaged mass increases from $0.172\\\\,m_{0}$ to $0.263\\\\,m_{0}$, which corresponds to an increase of approximately $57\\\\%$; for holes, the direction-averaged mass increases from $0.149\\\\,m_{0}$ to $0.265\\\\,m_{0}$, corresponding to an increase of approximately $79\\\\%$.\nTable I\n\n6. State the authors' interpretation: because the computed mass renormalizations are obtained by comparing band structures that (i) reproduce the same experimental band gap on the two structures by suitable choice of $\\\\alpha$ and (ii) differ only by the inclusion of finite-temperature atomic disorder (AIMD configuration vs ideal cubic lattice), the mass increases are attributed to thermal-lattice fluctuations rather than to the choice of $\\\\alpha$ or to polaron formation; this interpretation is supported by additional calculations in which applying $\\\\alpha=0.54$ to the ideal cubic lattice yields an underestimated gap and different masses, demonstrating that correct atomic structure (finite-temperature disorder) is the primary cause of the observed mass enhancement.\nFig. 2\n\n7. Conclude that thermal lattice fluctuations in $CsPbBr_{3}$ at $T=300\\\\,$K lead to large renormalizations of band-edge curvatures, specifically increasing the electron effective mass by approximately $57\\\\%$ and the hole effective mass by approximately $79\\\\%$, e.g., changing the direction-averaged hole mass from $m_h\\\\approx0.149\\\\,m_{0}$ (ideal cubic, $0\\\\,$K, $\\\\alpha=0.74$) to $m_h=0.265\\\\,m_{0}$ (AIMD, $300\\\\,$K, $\\\\alpha=0.54$).",
    prior=0.95,
)
